observationText: The Nf14F/Arg681*; DhhCre mice developed paralysis in one or both hind limbs starting around 4 months of age, with 55.6% exhibiting paralysis by 5 months. They also showed symptoms like lethargy, weight loss, dermatitis, and dehydration.
The Nf14F/Arg681*; DhhCre model displayed a robust tumor phenotype, with 81.5% of animals developing neurofibromas throughout their lifetime.

The Nf14F/Arg681*; DhhCre model showed an earlier onset of paralysis and tumorigenesis at 5 months compared to the previously described Nf131&32F/31&32F; DhhCre model, which exhibited paralysis in 28.6% of animals by 6 months.
By 5 months of age, 54.1% of the Nf14F/4F; DhhCre mice, another model generated in the same study, were paralyzed.
The Nf14F/Arg681* allele stimulated tumorigenesis when placed in context with a loss-of-function allele, as demonstrated by the tumor phenotype in the Nf14F/Arg681*; DhhCre mice.
